Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is data augmentation?
AI Response

Data augmentation artificially increases training data by applying transformations like rotation, cropping, and
flipping to existing samples, improving model generalization.

Example 1.2

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.

Example 1.3

User

What is transfer learning?
AI Response

Transfer learning reuses a model trained on one task as a starting point for another related task, reducing
training time and data requirements significantly.

Example 1.4

User

What is an epoch?
AI Response

An epoch is one full pass through the entire training dataset. Multiple epochs are used, and the number is a
key hyperparameter affecting model convergence.

Example 1.5

User

What is word embedding?
AI Response

Word embeddings map words to dense vectors where similar words are nearby. Word2Vec, GloVe, and
FastText are popular methods, used as NLP model input features.

Example 1.6

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.7

User

What is dropout?
AI Response



Dropout randomly sets a fraction of neuron activations to zero during training, preventing co-adaptation of
neurons and reducing overfitting.

Example 1.8

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response

Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.

Example 1.9

User

What is a confusion matrix?
AI Response

A confusion matrix shows counts of true/false positives and negatives for a classifier, enabling computation of
accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.

Example 1.10

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.



